            <div id="cite-apa" class="tab selected" role="tabpanel" aria-labelledby="tab-0" tabindex="-1" aria-hidden="true">
                <div class="rendering rendering_researchoutput  rendering_researchoutput_apa rendering_contributiontojournal rendering_apa rendering_contributiontojournal_apa">Diez-Perez, A., Naylor, K. E., Abrahamsen, B., Agnusdei, D., Brandi, M. L., Cooper, C., Dennison, E., Eriksen, E. F., Gold, D. T., Guanabens, N., Hadji, P.<a rel="Person" href="https://cris.maastrichtuniversity.nl/en/persons/micka%C3%ABl-hiligsmann/" class="link"><span>, Hiligsmann, M.</span></a>, Horne, R., Josse, R., Kanis, J. A., Obermayer-Pietsch, B., Prieto-Alhambra, D., Reginster, J. .-Y., Rizzoli, R., ... European Calcified Tissue Soc (2017). <a rel="ContributionToJournal" href="https://cris.maastrichtuniversity.nl/en/publications/international-osteoporosis-foundation-and-european-calcified-tiss/" class="link"><span>International Osteoporosis Foundation and European Calcified Tissue Society Working Group. Recommendations for the screening of adherence to oral bisphosphonates</span></a>. <a rel="Journal" href="#" class="link"><span><em>Osteoporosis International</em></span></a>, <em>28</em>(3), 767-774. <a onclick="window.open(this.href, '_blank','noopener,noreferrer'); return false;" href="https://doi.org/10.1007/s00198-017-3906-6" class="link"><span>https://doi.org/10.1007/s00198-017-3906-6</span></a></div>
            </div>
        
            <div id="cite-author" class="tab " role="tabpanel" aria-labelledby="tab-1" tabindex="-1" aria-hidden="true">
                <div class="rendering rendering_researchoutput  rendering_researchoutput_author rendering_contributiontojournal rendering_author rendering_contributiontojournal_author">Diez-Perez, A. ; Naylor, K. E. ; Abrahamsen, B. et al. / <a rel="ContributionToJournal" href="https://cris.maastrichtuniversity.nl/en/publications/international-osteoporosis-foundation-and-european-calcified-tiss/" class="link"><span><strong>International Osteoporosis Foundation and European Calcified Tissue Society Working Group. Recommendations for the screening of adherence to oral bisphosphonates</strong></span></a>. In: <a rel="Journal" href="#" class="link"><span>Osteoporosis International</span></a>. 2017 ; Vol. 28, No. 3. pp. 767-774.</div>
            </div>
        
            <div id="cite-BIBTEX" class="tab " role="tabpanel" aria-labelledby="tab-2" tabindex="-1" aria-hidden="true">
                <div class="rendering rendering_researchoutput  rendering_researchoutput_bibtex rendering_contributiontojournal rendering_bibtex rendering_contributiontojournal_bibtex"><div>@article{6b17bfecfbe14d548bf3c3bea9274ee3,</div><div>  title     = "International Osteoporosis Foundation and European Calcified Tissue Society Working Group. Recommendations for the screening of adherence to oral bisphosphonates",</div><div>  abstract  = "Adherence to oral bisphosphonates is low. A screening strategy is proposed based on the response of biochemical markers of bone turnover after 3 months of therapy. If no change is observed, the clinician should reassess the adherence to the treatment and also other potential issues with the drug.Low adherence to oral bisphosphonates is a common problem that jeopardizes the efficacy of treatment of osteoporosis. No clear screening strategy for the assessment of compliance is widely accepted in these patients.The International Osteoporosis Foundation and the European Calcified Tissue Society have convened a working group to propose a screening strategy to detect a lack of adherence to these drugs. The question to answer was whether the bone turnover markers (BTMs) PINP and CTX can be used to identify low adherence in patients with postmenopausal osteoporosis initiating oral bisphosphonates for osteoporosis. The findings of the TRIO study specifically address this question and were used as the basis for testing the hypothesis.Based on the findings of the TRIO study, specifically addressing this question, the working group recommends measuring PINP and CTX at baseline and 3 months after starting therapy to check for a decrease above the least significant change (decrease of more than 38\% for PINP and 56\% for CTX). Detection rate for the measurement of PINP is 84\%, for CTX 87\% and, if variation in at least one is considered when measuring both, the level of detection is 94.5\%.If a significant decrease is observed, the treatment can continue, but if no decrease occurs, the clinician should reassess to identify problems with the treatment, mainly low adherence.",</div><div>  keywords  = "Adherence, Bisphosphonates, Osteoporosis treatment, Position paper, Screening, BONE TURNOVER MARKERS, AUTOMATED SERUM ASSAY, POSTMENOPAUSAL OSTEOPOROSIS, BIOCHEMICAL MARKERS, I COLLAGEN, THERAPY, PERSISTENCE, HISTOMORPHOMETRY, WOMEN, RISK",</div><div>  author    = "A. Diez-Perez and Naylor, \{K. E.\} and B. Abrahamsen and D. Agnusdei and Brandi, \{M. L.\} and C. Cooper and E. Dennison and Eriksen, \{E. F.\} and Gold, \{D. T.\} and N. Guanabens and P. Hadji and M. Hiligsmann and R. Horne and R. Josse and Kanis, \{J. A.\} and B. Obermayer-Pietsch and D. Prieto-Alhambra and Reginster, \{J. -Y.\} and R. Rizzoli and S. Silverman and Zillikens, \{M. C.\} and R. Eastell and \{Int Osteoporosis Fdn\} and \{European Calcified Tissue Soc\}",</div><div>  year      = "2017",</div><div>  month     = mar,</div><div>  doi       = "10.1007/s00198-017-3906-6",</div><div>  language  = "English",</div><div>  volume    = "28",</div><div>  pages     = "767--774",</div><div>  journal   = "Osteoporosis International",</div><div>  issn      = "0937-941X",</div><div>  publisher = "Springer",</div><div>  number    = "3",</div><p>}</p></div>
            </div>
        
            <div id="cite-harvard" class="tab " role="tabpanel" aria-labelledby="tab-3" tabindex="-1" aria-hidden="true">
                <div class="rendering rendering_researchoutput  rendering_researchoutput_harvard rendering_contributiontojournal rendering_harvard rendering_contributiontojournal_harvard">Diez-Perez, A, Naylor, KE, Abrahamsen, B, Agnusdei, D, Brandi, ML, Cooper, C, Dennison, E, Eriksen, EF, Gold, DT, Guanabens, N, Hadji, P<a rel="Person" href="https://cris.maastrichtuniversity.nl/en/persons/micka%C3%ABl-hiligsmann/" class="link"><span>, Hiligsmann, M</span></a>, Horne, R, Josse, R, Kanis, JA, Obermayer-Pietsch, B, Prieto-Alhambra, D, Reginster, J-Y, Rizzoli, R, Silverman, S, Zillikens, MC, Eastell, R, Int Osteoporosis Fdn &amp; European Calcified Tissue Soc 2017, '<a rel="ContributionToJournal" href="https://cris.maastrichtuniversity.nl/en/publications/international-osteoporosis-foundation-and-european-calcified-tiss/" class="link harvard_title"><span>International Osteoporosis Foundation and European Calcified Tissue Society Working Group. Recommendations for the screening of adherence to oral bisphosphonates</span></a>', <a rel="Journal" href="#" class="link"><span><em>Osteoporosis International</em></span></a>, vol. 28, no. 3, pp. 767-774. <a onclick="window.open(this.href, '_blank','noopener,noreferrer'); return false;" href="https://doi.org/10.1007/s00198-017-3906-6" class="link"><span>https://doi.org/10.1007/s00198-017-3906-6</span></a></div>
            </div>
        
            <div id="cite-standard" class="tab " role="tabpanel" aria-labelledby="tab-4" tabindex="-1" aria-hidden="true">
                <div class="rendering rendering_researchoutput  rendering_researchoutput_standard rendering_contributiontojournal rendering_standard rendering_contributiontojournal_standard"><a rel="ContributionToJournal" href="https://cris.maastrichtuniversity.nl/en/publications/international-osteoporosis-foundation-and-european-calcified-tiss/" class="link"><span><strong>International Osteoporosis Foundation and European Calcified Tissue Society Working Group. Recommendations for the screening of adherence to oral bisphosphonates.</strong></span></a> / Diez-Perez, A.; Naylor, K. E.; Abrahamsen, B. et al. <br />In: <a rel="Journal" href="#" class="link"><span>Osteoporosis International</span></a>, Vol. 28, No. 3, 03.2017, p. 767-774.<p class="type"><span class="type_family">Research output<span class="type_family_sep">: </span></span><span class="type_classification_parent">Contribution to journal<span class="type_parent_sep"> › </span></span><span class="type_classification">Article</span><span class="type_classification"><span class="type_parent_sep"> › </span>Academic</span><span class="type_classification"><span class="type_parent_sep"> › </span>peer-review</span></p></div>
            </div>
        
            <div id="cite-RIS" class="tab " role="tabpanel" aria-labelledby="tab-5" tabindex="-1" aria-hidden="true">
                <div class="rendering rendering_researchoutput  rendering_researchoutput_ris rendering_contributiontojournal rendering_ris rendering_contributiontojournal_ris"><p>TY  - JOUR</p><p>T1  - International Osteoporosis Foundation and European Calcified Tissue Society Working Group. Recommendations for the screening of adherence to oral bisphosphonates</p><p>AU  - Diez-Perez, A.</p><p>AU  - Naylor, K. E.</p><p>AU  - Abrahamsen, B.</p><p>AU  - Agnusdei, D.</p><p>AU  - Brandi, M. L.</p><p>AU  - Cooper, C.</p><p>AU  - Dennison, E.</p><p>AU  - Eriksen, E. F.</p><p>AU  - Gold, D. T.</p><p>AU  - Guanabens, N.</p><p>AU  - Hadji, P.</p><p>AU  - Hiligsmann, M.</p><p>AU  - Horne, R.</p><p>AU  - Josse, R.</p><p>AU  - Kanis, J. A.</p><p>AU  - Obermayer-Pietsch, B.</p><p>AU  - Prieto-Alhambra, D.</p><p>AU  - Reginster, J. -Y.</p><p>AU  - Rizzoli, R.</p><p>AU  - Silverman, S.</p><p>AU  - Zillikens, M. C.</p><p>AU  - Eastell, R.</p><p>AU  - Int Osteoporosis Fdn</p><p>AU  - European Calcified Tissue Soc</p><p>PY  - 2017/3</p><p>Y1  - 2017/3</p><p>N2  - Adherence to oral bisphosphonates is low. A screening strategy is proposed based on the response of biochemical markers of bone turnover after 3 months of therapy. If no change is observed, the clinician should reassess the adherence to the treatment and also other potential issues with the drug.Low adherence to oral bisphosphonates is a common problem that jeopardizes the efficacy of treatment of osteoporosis. No clear screening strategy for the assessment of compliance is widely accepted in these patients.The International Osteoporosis Foundation and the European Calcified Tissue Society have convened a working group to propose a screening strategy to detect a lack of adherence to these drugs. The question to answer was whether the bone turnover markers (BTMs) PINP and CTX can be used to identify low adherence in patients with postmenopausal osteoporosis initiating oral bisphosphonates for osteoporosis. The findings of the TRIO study specifically address this question and were used as the basis for testing the hypothesis.Based on the findings of the TRIO study, specifically addressing this question, the working group recommends measuring PINP and CTX at baseline and 3 months after starting therapy to check for a decrease above the least significant change (decrease of more than 38% for PINP and 56% for CTX). Detection rate for the measurement of PINP is 84%, for CTX 87% and, if variation in at least one is considered when measuring both, the level of detection is 94.5%.If a significant decrease is observed, the treatment can continue, but if no decrease occurs, the clinician should reassess to identify problems with the treatment, mainly low adherence.</p><p>AB  - Adherence to oral bisphosphonates is low. A screening strategy is proposed based on the response of biochemical markers of bone turnover after 3 months of therapy. If no change is observed, the clinician should reassess the adherence to the treatment and also other potential issues with the drug.Low adherence to oral bisphosphonates is a common problem that jeopardizes the efficacy of treatment of osteoporosis. No clear screening strategy for the assessment of compliance is widely accepted in these patients.The International Osteoporosis Foundation and the European Calcified Tissue Society have convened a working group to propose a screening strategy to detect a lack of adherence to these drugs. The question to answer was whether the bone turnover markers (BTMs) PINP and CTX can be used to identify low adherence in patients with postmenopausal osteoporosis initiating oral bisphosphonates for osteoporosis. The findings of the TRIO study specifically address this question and were used as the basis for testing the hypothesis.Based on the findings of the TRIO study, specifically addressing this question, the working group recommends measuring PINP and CTX at baseline and 3 months after starting therapy to check for a decrease above the least significant change (decrease of more than 38% for PINP and 56% for CTX). Detection rate for the measurement of PINP is 84%, for CTX 87% and, if variation in at least one is considered when measuring both, the level of detection is 94.5%.If a significant decrease is observed, the treatment can continue, but if no decrease occurs, the clinician should reassess to identify problems with the treatment, mainly low adherence.</p><p>KW  - Adherence</p><p>KW  - Bisphosphonates</p><p>KW  - Osteoporosis treatment</p><p>KW  - Position paper</p><p>KW  - Screening</p><p>KW  - BONE TURNOVER MARKERS</p><p>KW  - AUTOMATED SERUM ASSAY</p><p>KW  - POSTMENOPAUSAL OSTEOPOROSIS</p><p>KW  - BIOCHEMICAL MARKERS</p><p>KW  - I COLLAGEN</p><p>KW  - THERAPY</p><p>KW  - PERSISTENCE</p><p>KW  - HISTOMORPHOMETRY</p><p>KW  - WOMEN</p><p>KW  - RISK</p><p>U2  - 10.1007/s00198-017-3906-6</p><p>DO  - 10.1007/s00198-017-3906-6</p><p>M3  - Article</p><p>SN  - 0937-941X</p><p>VL  - 28</p><p>SP  - 767</p><p>EP  - 774</p><p>JO  - Osteoporosis International</p><p>JF  - Osteoporosis International</p><p>IS  - 3</p><p>ER  - </p></div>
            </div>
        
